  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "Does Java support Multiple Inheritance?",
  "response": "No, Java does **not support multiple inheritance** for classes. This means a class in Java cannot directly inherit from **more than one class**. The primary reason for this design decision is to avoid the **diamond problem**, which can lead to ambiguity and complexity in the code.\n\n### Why Java Doesn't Support Multiple Inheritance\nConsider the following scenario:\n\n```java\nclass A {\n    void method() {\n        System.out.println(\"A\");\n    }\n}\n\nclass B {\n    void method() {\n        System.out.println(\"B\");\n    }\n}\n\n// If multiple inheritance were allowed, this would cause ambiguity\nclass C extends A, B {\n}\n```\n\nIf class `C` inherits from both `A` and `B`, and both have a `method()`, it would be unclear which `method()` to call when invoking `C.method()`. This is known as the **diamond problem**.\n\n---\n\n### How Java Addresses the Need for Multiple Inheritance\nJava provides alternatives to achieve similar functionality:\n\n1. **Interfaces**:\n   - A class can implement **multiple interfaces**. Interfaces allow you to define behavior (methods) without implementation, enabling a form of multiple inheritance.\n   - Example:\n     ```java\n     interface A {\n         void methodA();\n     }\n\n     interface B {\n         void methodB();\n     }\n\n     class C implements A, B {\n         public void methodA() {\n             System.out.println(\"A\");\n         }\n         public void methodB() {\n             System.out.println(\"B\");\n         }\n     }\n     ```\n\n2. **Default Methods in Interfaces** (Java 8+):\n   - Interfaces can now have default methods, providing partial implementation. This allows sharing behavior across classes without multiple inheritance.\n   - Example:\n     ```java\n     interface A {\n         default void method() {\n             System.out.println(\"A\");\n         }\n     }\n\n     interface B {\n         default void method() {\n             System.out.println(\"B\");\n         }\n     }\n\n     class C implements A, B {\n         // Override to resolve ambiguity\n         public void method() {\n             A.super.method(); // Explicitly call A's method\n         }\n     }\n     ```\n\n3. **Composition over Inheritance**:\n   - Instead of inheriting from multiple classes, you can use composition (embedding instances of other classes) to achieve similar functionality.\n   - Example:\n     ```java\n     class A {\n         void methodA() {\n             System.out.println(\"A\");\n         }\n     }\n\n     class B {\n         void methodB() {\n             System.out.println(\"B\");\n         }\n     }\n\n     class C {\n         private A a = new A();\n         private B b = new B();\n\n         void methodA() {\n             a.methodA();\n         }\n         void methodB() {\n             b.methodB();\n         }\n     }\n     ```\n\n---\n\n### Summary\nJava avoids multiple inheritance for classes to prevent complexity and ambiguity. Instead, it encourages the use of **interfaces**, **default methods**, and **composition** to achieve similar functionality.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
